  I feel that if I take my time with the intention of never making a mistake, the progress per unit of time will be surprisingly fast, but "never making a mistake" is not realistic because mistakes can occur due to minor timing differences, and I am not sure how to reconcile these two feelings.
  At first, I was thinking, "Let's type three times each," and then I would go on to the next example sentence when I had typed it correctly three times. As the time got longer and longer, cases of not restarting three times in a row came up, and I unconsciously loosened up, thinking, "Three times is a total.
  The "total number of successes" is a futile [vanity measure]. Even if the success rate is 10%, if you do it 30 times, you will have an average of 3 total successes.
  Setting the total number of success attempts as a KPI creates a bias toward increasing the number of attempts rather than increasing the probability of success.
  By having easy loopholes that repeat a lot without using your head, you lose the incentive to use your head to increase your chances of success.
